{"id":"1709.07052","submitter":"Eliahu Cohen","authors":"Yakir Aharonov, Eliahu Cohen, Jeff Tollaksen","title":"A Completely Top-Down Hierarchical Structure in Quantum Mechanics","comments":"6 pages, 1 figure, comments are welcome","journal-ref":"Proc. Natl. Acad. Sci. USA 115(46), 11730-11735 (2018)","doi":"10.1073/pnas.1807554115","report-no":null,"categories":"quant-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Can a large system be fully characterized using its subsystems via inductive\nreasoning? Is it possible to completely reduce the behavior of a complex system\nto the behavior of its simplest \"atoms\"? In the following paper we answer these\nquestions on the negative for a specific class of systems and measurements. We\nbegin with simple two-particle example, where strong correlations arise between\ntwo apparently empty boxes. This leads to new surprising effects within atomic\nand electromagnetic systems. A general construction based on pre- and\npost-selected ensembles is then suggested, where the N-body correlation can be\ngenuinely perceived as a global property, as long as one is limited to\npreforming a small set of measurements which we term \"strictly local\". We\nconclude that within time-symmetric quantum mechanics and under certain\nboundary conditions, high-order correlations can determine low-order ones, but\nnot vice versa. Moreover, the latter seem to provide no information at all\nregarding the former. This supports a top-down structure in many-body quantum\nmechanics.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 20 Sep 2017 19:59:59 GMT"}],"update_date":"2018-11-19"}
